<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Environmental Audit Committee</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by AES Southern Ltd</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Declaration of interest</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">AES Southern Ltd </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are a leading sustainability company providing consultancy and assessment services to the new build domestic market in relation to the Code for Sustainable Homes and are accredited to do so with both the BRE and STROMA</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">AES Southern Ltd</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">AES Southern Ltd </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">was established in 2005 as a direct </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">response to demand from developers for independent, practical advice </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on delivering sustainable developments in line with current and future regulations, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">which they could rely on. Keeping this at the heart of everything we do, AES Southern has grown to become a leading sustainability consultancy to the new build industry in the UK. We work with a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">broad </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">range of clients including top 10 UK developers, delivering an end to end service from pre-acquisition and planning advice to on-site post construction assessment and certification. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Our portfolio of services to both</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> residential an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d non-residential developments include</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> strategy documents, SAP, SBEM, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">CfSH</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, BREEAM, psi value calculations and overheating risk analysis.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We are actively involved in a number of industry groups such as the HBF and Zero Carbon Hub, providing insight and responses </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">based on our knowledge and experience </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to key consultations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Currently we are represented on 4 working groups advising the ZCH in regards to the Industry and government sponsored project on “Closing the gap between design and as-built performance”</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Our highly experienced team of consultants shares a passion for developing their technical expertise </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">whilst promoting sustainable design</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. We engage with the wider industry to keep abreast of the issues that matter to our clients and make sure the advice we are giving is up to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">date.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Through our engagement with projects at an early stage we are able to propose energy and sustainability strategies that we know are deliverable. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We believe that the Code for sustainable homes has provided an excellent platform for driving sustainability in the built and associated environment, and by doing so, has been the catalyst for significant investment in technological advances and innovation as well as providing structure for developers, suppliers and manufacturers</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Comments</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Whilst AES Southern</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">understands and supports </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the Government’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">aim </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to simplify the current raft of  standards and regulations </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to reduce bureaucracy and cost to developer</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">support growth whilst delivering quality, sustainability, safety and accessibility </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="I" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">However, the o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">verview seems to be suggesting  that the government’s intention is that rather than local planning authorities adopting their own approaches they will be forced to adopt ‘nationally described standards’ which they will only </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">adopt if ‘they are strictly necessary and justifiable’</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  It also seems to suggest that a single, Building Regulation based national standard is not the preferred approach as this would lead to ‘an average of likely requirements across the country, and therefore could have adverse impacts on viability if too costly in some places while not meeting the nation’s needs in the other.’ </span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">With regard to Energy only the proposal seems to be that the only target will be that described in the building regulations. ‘There will no longer have to be detailed and lengthy discussions on whether additional requirements are viable or not – as there will be one clear set of standards for new homes to meet.’ </span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> There will be a ‘Building Regulations only approach to energy standards’ </span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">If a single national standard could have adverse impacts on viability if too costly in some places while not meeting the nation’s needs in the other, then why is it the preferred approach for Energy? Should there not be higher standards for different areas where profit margins allow the developer to invest more into reducing CO2? </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">On the 30</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> July, the Government announced the changes to Part L of the Building Regulations and set out the energy performance target of 6% improvement over 2010 standards across the build mix. This falls below the current Code 4 level of 44% improvement from 2006 Part L and would prevent </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">local authorities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> from being proactive in asking for higher standards in areas where it would be considered technically, environmentally and economically viable to do so. In our view and based on experience, the lowest common denominator will always be followed and would </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">not necessarily drive up energy performance standards.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffff00; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Local Government Association stated in responding to the draft NPPF: “LGA</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> believes the NPPF should not restrict local authorities from setting local standards that exceed minimum </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">national standards where these would be supported by evidence to demonstrate that they are achievable and viable.”</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We are also concerned that developing a nationally described set of standards to cover only the areas outlined in the housing standards review and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">“winding down” of the Code for Sustainable Homes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> would exclude any independent assessment of areas such as ecology and materials and as a consequence reduce the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">scope for improving the sustainability of new housing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> thereby working against one of the primary aims of the review.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The National Planning Policy Framework states that “to achieve sustainable development economic, social and environmental gains should be sought jointly and simultaneously”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> However, no account within the impact assessment is made regarding any </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">wider and longer term economic, social and e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nvironmental costs or benefits but concentrates on upfront costs to developer.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 23.91pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Local Government Association stated in responding to the draft NPPF: “LGA believes the NPPF should not restrict local authorities from setting local standards that exceed minimum national standards where these would be supported by evidence to demonstrate that they are achievable and viable.”</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Code has allowed local authorities to form policies in their local plans that can reflect the requirements and aspirations of the local area specific to its circumstances.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As a company we deal with developments across the length and breadth of England and are aware of many local authorities that have policies within their adopted local plans that require new housing to achieve a Code level. Whilst the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">proposals </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">claim</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> aim to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> simplify the current framework</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> it is more likely to create more uncertainty, confusion and delay within the whole industry which in turn may lead to additional </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">costs not yet foreseen.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e Code</span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">delivers a distinct advantage</span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to local authorities</span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in that the determination of compliance and the driving force behind it is by independent assessment by trained and licensed third party professionals.  Therefore, Local Authorities can be re-assured and not have costs associated or resources committed to assessing compliance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> themselves</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> And as the Code covers a wide range of sustainability issues Local Authorities can, and have already, dropped separate local standards such as the “Merton Rule” in favour of a higher Code level such as Code 4 </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As mentioned above, the Code is not one standard but groups many different standards together with the aim of protecting the environment and encouraging the construction of high performance homes sustainably. As it covers various standards in one place if used correctly by all parties can reduce red tape.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We are mindful that any future changes to the current process will  need to pay particular attention to transitional arrangements and account for areas such as:</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 67.78pt; padding-left:4.22pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The large number of developments already registered for a Code assessment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> As a company, we are currently dealing with a total of 96 developments where 6099 units are required to meet a Code level.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 68.33pt; padding-left:3.67pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">L</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ocal planning authorities which have local plans with policies requiring compliance with the Code for Sustainable Homes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 67.1pt; padding-left:4.9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The potential impact on businesses and individual professionals who are qualified and licensed Code assessors.  </span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="I" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 24.41pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Consideration and suggestions moving forward</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 24.09pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">While we agree with the principle of simplifying the current system of regulations and standards, it is critical that we maintain the momentum towards building sustainable new housing and continue the cycle of innovation in the construction industry that ultimately leads to reduced costs in the supply chain.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The way forward must take into account current policy and any contractual obligations in regard to the Code for Sustainable Homes. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 24.09pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A possible way forward could be to update and streamline the Code for Sustainable Homes as a nationally prescribed standard that the whole industry is familiar with.  Thereby setting a single framework with tiered standards that sit alongside of regulations. This would then cover issues at a local level regarding constraints, viability, local circumstances and aspiration.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 27.11pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Again, as has already been recognised, the Code has, and could continue to lead the direction of travel in relation to future regulations.  As so many local plans currently specify the Code it would avoid disruption to the planning system.   </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">[Date]</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> DCLG, Housing Standards Review, August 2013, Paragraph 31</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> DCLG, Housing Standards Review, August 2013, Paragraph 27</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> DCLG, Housing Standards Review, August 2013, Paragraph 231</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> DCLG, Housing Standards Review, August 2013, Paragraph 232</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">LGA response to draft National Planning Policy Framework</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> 17 October 2011</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> National Planning Policy Framework, March 2012, paragraph 8</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn7"></a><a href="#_ftnref7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">LGA response to draft National Planning Policy Framework</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> 17 October 2011</span></p></body></html>